<meta property="og:description" content="Suppose you’re the minister of education in a lower-middle income country. It’s budget season. You have a meeting tomorrow with the finance minister to make your case for more education spending. You know she’s skeptical that money is really what’s holding your school system back. The World Bank says that &quot;public spending does not correlate strongly with learning,&quot; and &quot;improvements in learning are unlikely when additional resources are allocated like past funding.&quot; You’re going to need to persuade her. So what’s your pitch? Are there shovel-ready investments that your ministry is prepared to roll out next fiscal year, where money is credibly the binding constraint?" />
